# Agent Onboarding

Read this first when spinning up a fresh context. You should be able to
go from "I don't know anything" to "working on my tasks" in about 15
minutes.

## 1. Know the system (~2 min)

Read [README.md](README.md) and [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md). You'll learn:
- The coordination system has multiple workstreams. Each has its own file.
- You're an agent with a `@tag`. Other agents address you by that tag.
- Your personal notes live in `scratchboards/<your_tag>/main.md`.
- When you finish a task, flip `@tag` → `#tag`.

## 2. Understand the project (~10 min, REQUIRED)

Read {{PROJECT_DOC_PATH}} — **the whole file**. Even bug-fix agents
need this context. You can't meaningfully fix a part of a system
without knowing what the whole system does.

> **TODO when scaffolding:** replace `{{PROJECT_DOC_PATH}}` above with
> the actual path to this project's main architecture / overview doc
> (e.g. `architecture.md`, `docs/overview.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`). If
> the project has no such doc, list the top-level entry points instead
> (`README.md`, `src/main.py`, etc.) — but consider writing one.

After reading, you should be able to answer the basic "what does this
project do, what are its major components, what are the hard
constraints" questions. If you can't, re-read. Don't skip this step —
it's the difference between "I changed code that compiles" and "I
changed code that fits the system."

## 3. Find your work (~1 min)

```
tayfa-inbox <your_tag>
```

This lists:
- Open tasks addressed to you (unchecked `[ ]` in `Tasks — @<tag>` sections)
- Open bugs addressed to you
- Unresolved memos addressed to you

Everything comes with file:line refs so you can jump straight to
context. If your inbox is empty, ask the user what they want you to do.

## 4. Read your scratchboard (~1 min)

```
dev/coordination/scratchboards/<your_tag>/main.md
```

Your own notes from prior sessions. Plans, half-formed thoughts, links
you gathered, things you decided but didn't finish writing up.

## 5. Read the workstream's coordination file (~3 min)

The inbox output tells you which coordination file(s) your work lives
in. Read the **Current Sprint** section for the overall goal, then
skim the other agents' tasks so you know what's happening around you.
Don't read the entire file — it has historical change log and past
sprint notes you can ignore.

## 6. Read the specs linked from your task (varies)

Your task entries in the coordination file should link to specs or
design docs. Those are the design contract — read the ones your work
touches.

## Opening ritual (summary)

```bash
cat dev/coordination/README.md
cat dev/coordination/AGENTS.md
cat {{PROJECT_DOC_PATH}}                       # REQUIRED, not optional
tayfa-inbox <your_tag>
cat dev/coordination/scratchboards/<your_tag>/main.md
# ...then the workstream file and linked specs
```

## When you're done

1. Flip `@tag` → `#tag` on completed items
2. Add a one-line entry to the workstream's Change Log
3. Update your scratchboard with anything future-you should remember
4. If you resolved a memo addressed to you, strike it through with `~~`
   only after ALL addressed agents have flipped their tags to `#`

## When you're stuck

- Post a memo in the relevant coordination file tagged at the agent who
  can unblock you.
- If the blocker is a design decision, tag the design owner.
- Don't silently wait — memos are the explicit async channel.
